  <div slot="quick-answer">
    <p><strong>Quick Answer:</strong> Good natural wine usually costs about $22 to $45. The best value is often in the upper-$20s to low-$40s. Above that, you should expect real producer identity and cleaner execution, not just funk and hype.</p>
  </div>

  <h2>What Natural Wine Should Actually Cost</h2>
  <p>Natural wine pricing is messy because it mixes genuine small-scale production costs with fashion markup. Some bottles cost more because they come from careful farming, low-volume production, and difficult cellar work. Others cost more because the bottle signals scene value. The whole point of this guide is to tell those two apart.</p>

  <h2>Best Value Bands</h2>
  <p><strong>$18 to $25</strong> can be fine, but it is the riskiest tier. This is where you are most likely to find bottles that are more concept than pleasure. <strong>$25 to $40</strong> is the real value zone. This is where natural wine starts to feel like serious wine rather than a novelty. <strong>$40 to $60</strong> should buy you more precision, site character, and producer reliability. Above that, only spend when you know the producer or the style you want.</p>

  <h2>Benchmark Bottles by Price</h2>
